Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: CPC, Neimeth, Oando Move

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-23T15:47:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-23/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-cocoa-processing-co-neimeth.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell for a
fifth day, dropping 0.5 percent to 60.24 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi, the capital. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index declined for a third day, slumping 2.4 percent to
20,202.52 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a
statement on the bourse’s  website .  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  slid 0.8 percent to 769.05 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. In Mauritius, the SEMDEX Index fell for a second day,
dropping 1.6 percent to 1,856.70 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port
Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index declined 0.6
percent to 1,108.19 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Cocoa Processing Co. (CPC GN), a Ghanaian chocolate maker,
fell 1 pesewa, or 33 percent, to 2 pesewas. Cocoa supplies will
exceed demand for the season starting Oct. 1, dashing forecasts
just last month for a shortage, a Bloomberg survey showed.  Oando Plc (OANDO)  , a Nigerian  oil company , fell to its
lowest since November 2003, declining 90 kobo, or 3.6 percent,
to 24.4 naira. Oil sank to the lowest level in more than six
weeks as a pledge by Group of 20 nations to tackle rising risks
failed to ease concern the global economy is on the brink of
another recession.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
 sgunnion@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
